Apr 15 2008 	An awful experience	I stayed in this hotel a few years ago now but the experience will stay with me for a lifetime. I booked a double room with en-suite for the Albion House Hotel also on Argyle Square. When we arrived at the hotel a sign on the door instructed as to cross the square to the Melville Hotel to check in. During the check in process, I was asked to pay in advance for the room and my credit card disappeared to a back room for about 10 minutes which was worrying. We were handed a key and told our room was on the first floor so we made for the door to head back over to the Albion House hotel. Imagine my surprise when the receptionist started to laugh and told us that we were staying in this hotel, not the Albion. I was slightly puzzled about the change of hotel but was informed that the Albion had no spare rooms. I had booked the hotel online over a month in advance so couldn't quite understand why my booking was accepted if there was no room there. We made our way up the stairs to the first floor to discover the room from hell. The double bed took up the whole room and I couldn't even open my suitcase fully to unpack. The cupboard door was hanging off it's hinges but you couldn't fully open the door anyway due to the bed being in the way. The TV only tuned into BBC2 but the picture was green and fuzzy. The decor was disgusting, old and in need of a total revamp. The room was so small that two people couldn't stand in the room without touching. And where was the en-suite? The 'en-suite' was just outside the door and serviced four other rooms as well. There was no toilet paper in the WC and the shower was disgusting &amp; only provided cold water. We didn't bother with the complimentary breakfast as you had to cross the square to another hotel to sample it. Early on a November morning with the traditional English rain, it's the last thing you want to do.  The staff were rude when I complained about the standard of the room. It then became very obvious why I was charged for my stay before I had seen the room. Due to finances we had no choice but to stay in this awful room for the full three nights we had booked.	
Dec 17 2007 	A bargain hotel	I was really worried when I read these reviews after I had booked myself and my parents into this hotel so we went there expecting the worse, but it was absolutley fine! It was clean and newly decorated with fully functioning locks on all bedroom and bathroom doors. The staff were friendly and helpful and although breakfast is basic, I think it's an added bonus for the price. The only criticism we had were that the rooms and the beds were quite small. I would recommend this hotel for anyone who needs somewhere cheap and cheerful to rest their head for a night or two.	
Sep 20 2007 	A better review	I stayed at the Meville for about a month while looking for a flat in London and I found it was perfectly ok for that purpose. The family who run the place actually gave me a discount as I was staying longterm and the fridge and use of the kitchen (although I admit it was basic with a 2 cookers that didnt really work but you're lucky to find that in London) was invaluable.First of all this is a budget hotel - you wont find prices like this in London so it will be basic. If you are looking anything other than okay place to sleep at night go elsewhere. I stayed in a double room (for single price) the first night, which was a little cruddy but okay and the second single room I stayed in was small but clean. They are cleaned daily as are the showers and toilets which I thought were fine( believe me I felt lucky as I had stayed in a young hostel the night before!) The beds were comfy and you get a tv and fridge. There is also a free wireless internet connection in that area too which is very useful. The breakfast was fine but again basic.I understand other peoples concerns about leaving luggage but honestly you cant get into the place without a key or being buzzed in (a fact that is annoying when you are trying to ask for a room!) I was nervous at first but for my part I found it safe and I stayed there on my own for a month! The manager and family were also quite friendly once you got chatting to them and he even let me send a fax from his office. I also believe you can trust their credit card system too and I often went into the office at the back to pay with my card - I think its just where they have the machine though it does seem abit of an odd place to have it.As much as I am grateful for the help I received at this hotel I would have to agree with some of the negative reports too. The staff can be rude and defensive (I experienced this again recently) which is annoying. The stairs are bad and you need to take your time and be careful with them. The hotel is abit shabby and needs updating but as I said - its good for the price. However the one thing that makes me hestitate about going back there is I did find a bedbug in my room and that is unacceptable.I hope this review has been helpful and good luck with which ever hotel you choose. Remember that there are loads of hotels on that street and the surrounding ones of the same or high level but I would strongly advise booking in advance.	
