Apr 14 2007	Brochure promises and their real meaning.	We happened to be at the Melville Hotel (London) last Easter and it took 5 days for us to (mis)interpret the information written on the website and the brochure.FACILITIES·Linen Included- Actually it must have sat there from the very beginning. The sheets were all dirty and shabby. Going to bed after a long day wandering round the city wasn’t really pleasant.·Credit Cards Accepted- The thing is that upon arrival you are sort of obliged to give your visa or whatever to the staff who will take it to another room coming back a few minutes later with the credit card and the invoice (dodgy!).·Towels- You are given 1 towel for your face and body that won’t be changed IN ANY CASE!!. ·Luggage Storage- Yes. Leave it anywhere in the hotel so burglars can take care of it (the staff doesn't).·Children Friendly- You have to be very heartless to confine them to this place for even 1 night.·Nice staff- OK, Coackroaches do not count, they are not part of the staff.·Guest Kitchen- It lacks knifes for example, but given that the staff is really rude and they spend most of the time wandering around the kitchen maybe it’s better like this.·Telephone/Fax Facilities- Were they?·24 Hour Reception- Meaning that you are given the key for the room and main gate. ·Travel Desk/Travel Info- Info??? All they say is when you have to check out, by 10:30 am. Travel info: There are some leaflets at the reception, which luckily I visited only once upon arrival, such as the one on the Jack the ripper experience but after 1 night at the Melville NOTHING can be more terrifying! ·No Lockout: Well, actually we couldn’t lock the door of our room, it didn’t work. Do they mean that?·No Smoking: Nobody will notice anyway (Stinks)·Smoking Rooms: See comment above.·24 hours check in: This is a bit confusing to me because I couldn’t check in before 2 pm.Other facilities not mentioned on the website: ·Coffin-like wardrobes (just in case).·You don’t need to bother in case of fire because there are no signs showing the way out.·Autobiographic carpets- You can literally read in them what former guests have eaten!·Therapeutic beds- perfect if you want a sick leave! ·Shower: 1 for 20 people, but not sure it really is. Looks like a gas chamber.·WC: 1 for 20 people. There was a hole in the door. Suppose it’s used for checking out whether the WC is really vacant (??!!!).	
Feb 11 2007 	Most miserable "hotel" I have ever experienced.	There are so, so many negative things to say about this positively disgusting hotel, I feel I need to divide my review into sections so as to avoid befuddling the reader! So...allow me to recount the many horrors...On arrival: you can't book in until 2 pm. For those arriving in the morning, this is a real problem as there is no safe place to leave one's luggage; you simply leave it in the rather unappealing reception area. Also, when booking in, I paid by credit card (in advance!), and was nervous about the manner in which my card was taken from me, into another room, and then returned to me along with a receipt for me to sign. Might sound like a trifle, but given the immediate negative impression I formed of the place, it made me really uncomfortable.Rooms: There are no elevators. Neither is there anyone to help you with your luggage. So you haul what luggage you have to your room via the stairs, which are dangerous. There are exposed carpet grippers on the steps, which could very easily pierce unsuspecting feet. The rooms themselves are disgusting. Really, truly disgusting. The carpets are utterly filthy. I would have been afraid to set an un-shod foot on them. The beds are ancient, creaky, and plain dirty. The rooms have fridges, but the inches of grime they've accumulated over the many years since they were last washed would discourage one to actually put any food in them. Similarly with the tea/coffee-making facilities. All of the above, however, was positively sanitary compared to the sink in my (first) room. It was blocked solid, and caked in all manner of grime and gloop. It was so gut-wrenching that I was actually afraid to brush my teeth or wash my face there (I had to go upstairs to use the sink in my friend's room!). Lastly, I had booked a single room, and when I arrived, was put in a twin room. It was not mentioned to me at the time of my arrival that someone had made a mess of my booking, and so I was told on the second morning, as I was on my way out, that I would have to change rooms. Bathrooms: I stayed here on a trip to London with a friend. When we arrived, we were put in rooms on two separate floors. Each floor has 1 shower and 1 WC which serve all rooms on that floor. On the day of our arrival, I found that the shower on my floor (and I don't need to mention at this stage that it was disgustingly dirty) had no hot water supply. The WC on that same floor had no light. On the second night, after my change of room, I was moved to the same floor as my friend. The WC was functional and lit (but filthy), but the door didn't lock properly. And the shower really was the stuff of nightmares. Again, the lock on the door wasn't entirely reliable, and it was even more dirty than the shower on the other floor. Gruesome. Staff: the staff are not helpful at all. Some are downright unpleasant. They tried to make a compliment of moving me to a room on the same floor as my friend on the second night of our stay!Atmosphere: As, by now, you will have gathered, this hotel is dangerously dirty. They offer a continental breakfast, but neither of us was willing to risk eating in this place. Furthermore, it was genuinely difficult to get to sleep there, due the endless noise from the street below. This was a problem particularly on the first night, when a group of idiots spent the night on the steps of the hotel drinking, shouting and bothering passing women. Notably, the staff of the Melville did nothing about this.All in all, I urge anyone who reads this to avoid the Melville at all costs. The money you'll save won't compensate you for the sheer misery you'll be subjected to here!	
